[[File:Byzantine Constantinople-en.png|right|250px|thumb|Map of Byzantine Constantinople. The Toklu Dede Mescidi is located in the northernmost part of the walled city, north of the [[Church of St. Mary of Blachernae (Istanbul)|Church of St. Mary of Blachernae]].]] '''''Toklu Dede Mosque''''' ({{lang-tr|Toklu Dede Mescidi}}, where ''mescit'' is the Turkish word for a small mosque), was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] [[mosque]] in [[Istanbul]], Turkey.<ref name=mw206>Müller-Wiener (1977), p. 206.</ref> The building was originally a [[Byzantine]] [[Eastern Orthodox]] church of unknown dedication.<ref name=mw206/> It was almost completely destroyed in 1929.<ref name=mw206/><ref name=tayprojpg41>{{Citation |url=http://tayproject.org/downloads/Rap/Dest_Rep_08_Mar_Byz.pdf |title=Archaeological Destructıon in Turkey, preliminary report |work=Marmara Region&nbsp;– Byzantine |publisher=TAY Project |page=29 |accessdate=April 13, 2012 }}</ref>
==Location== The edifice lay in [[Istanbul]], in the district of [[Fatih]], in the neighborhood ({{lang-tr|[[Mahalle]]}}) of [[Ayvansaray, Istanbul|Ayvansaray]]. The only remaining part of the building&nbsp;– the south wall&nbsp;– is enclosed in a modern house at ''Toklu Ibrahim Dede Sokak'', a few meters inside the [[walls of Constantinople|walled]] city, a short distance from the shore of the [[Golden Horn]], at the junction between the [[Blachernae]] wall and the largely pulled down [[Golden Horn]] walls.
===Byzantine Age=== The origin of this building, which was erected at the northern foot of the [[Seven hills of Istanbul|sixth hill]] of [[Constantinople]] in the neighborhood of ''ta Karianou'',<ref name=jamap>Janin (1953), Map of Constantinople</ref> part of the [[Blachernae]] quarter, is obscure. The small shrine lay on the inner side of the Wall of [[Heraclius]], less than 100 m west of the now demolished Gate of Küçük Ayvansaray (in Greek the Koiliomene Gate) of the [[Walls_of_Constantinople#Golden_Horn_Wall|Golden Horn Walls]], and east of the [[Walls_of_constantinople#Walls_of_Blachernae|Gate of Blachernae]].<ref name=mw302>Müller-Wiener (1977), p. 302.</ref> The church,&nbsp;– in common with the nearby [[Atik Mustafa Pasha Mosque]], also originally a Byzantine church&nbsp;– has been identified with Saint Thekla of the Palace of [[Blachernae]] ([[Greek language|Greek]]: {{lang|grc|Άγία Θέκλα τοῦ Παλατίου τῶν Βλαχερνών}}, ''Hagia Thekla tou Palatiou tōn Vlakhernōn'').<ref name=ey66> According to Semavi Eyice the building could be identified with the church of the Saints Priskos and Nikolaos, a 6th-century foundation. Eyice (1955) p. 66</ref> However, the building lay too far from the [[Blachernae Palace]], so that this identification, based only on the similarity of the name, should be rejected.<ref name=ja148>Janin (1953), p. 148.</ref> Stylistically the church belongs to the [[Komnenian era]] (middle/second half of the 11th century).<ref name=mw206/><ref name=kr409>Krautheimer (1986), p. 409</ref> At the beginning of the 14th century&nbsp;– in the [[Palaiologan era]]&nbsp;– the church underwent minor architectonic changes and its [[fresco]] decoration was renewed.<ref name=mw206/> [[File:Naos tis Hagias Theklis.jpg|right|250px|thumb|The mosque viewed from northeast in a drawing of 1877, from A.G. Paspates' ''Byzantine topographical studies'']]
===Ottoman and Turkish Age=== After the [[Fall of Constantinople]] to the Ottomans in 1453, between the end of the 15th and the beginning of the 16th century the church was converted into a small mosque (Mescid) by Toklu Ibrahim Dede, a former soldier of [[Mehmed II|Mehmed the Conqueror]],<ref name=gul248>Gülersoy (1976), p. 248</ref> who was the custodian of the nearby ''[[türbe]]'' of Ebû Șeybet ül Hudrî, like the more famous [[Abu Ayyub al-Ansari]] (the standard bearer of [[Muhammad]]), a [[Ansar (Islam)|companion]] of the Prophet.<ref name=mw206/> Both died during the [[Siege of Constantinople (674–678)|first Arab siege of Constantinople]] and were buried outside the wall of Heraclius. The ''türbe'' of Ebû Șeybet ül Hudrî is now placed in the citadel between the Wall of Heraclius and that of [[Leo V the Armenian|Leo the Armenian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://istanbulholidays.blogspot.com/2011/02/walls-of-leo-and-heraclius.html|accessdate=20 April 2012|publisher=istanbulholidays.blogspot.com|title=Walls of Leo and Heraclius}}</ref>
In 1929 the owner of the building demolished it almost completely, leaving in place only the south wall and the apse. With the demolition the paintings, whose existence was known since 1890, came again to light. The first surveying of the remains occurred in 1954. <ref name=mw206/> As of 2012, only the surviving south wall, enclosed in a new building, and the name of the road where it once lay remember the small edifice.
==Description==
The building had a rectangular plan with external sides of 14.2 m and 6.7 m.<ref name=mw206/> A square single [[Cella|nave]] was surmounted by a [[barrel vault]] and covered at its center by a dome with a diameter of about 4 m.<ref name=kr409/><ref name=os23>Ousterhout (1987), p.23</ref> This was supported by arches carried by angular piers.<ref name=os23/> The nave was preceded by an [[Narthex|esonarthex]] and ended towards East with a [[bema]] and a polygonal [[apse]] adorned internally and externally with shallow niches.<ref name=mw206/><ref name=kr409/><ref name=mw207>Müller Wiener (1977), p. 207</ref> The plan of the building is similar on a reduced size to that of the [[Chora Church]].<ref name=os23/> The edifice's [[brickwork]] consisted of courses of rows of white stones alternating with rows of red [[brick]]s. The external wall were divided with half pillars and with [[lesene]]s surmounted by arches. <ref name=kr409/> The church was decorated with 14th-century frescoes, among them images of the Saints [[Pope Eleuterus|Eleuterus]], [[Saint Abercius|Abercius]], [[Saint Polykarpos|Polykarpos]], [[Saint Spyridon|Spyridon]], [[Procopius of Scythopolis|Procopius]] and [[Nicetas of Remesiana|Nicetas]], some of them framed in [[Medaillon (architecture)|medallions]]. The barrel vault above the altar was decorated with a fresco representing the [[Nativity of Jesus in art|Nativity of Jesus]].<ref name=mw206/>
